elatively lower revenue scale") because its capacity is primarily absorbed by internal needs for Connectivity and AI, highlighting its foundational, strategic role.\n\n### **Summary Table of Interdependencies**\n\n| From Segment | To Segment | Nature of Interdependency | Financial Treatment |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | **Connectivity** | Provides launch capacity for Starlink satellites. | Costs capitalized in Connectivity segment; **no intersegment revenue** for Space. |\n| **Space** | **AI** | Expected to provide significant future launch capacity. | Costs expected to be capitalized in AI segment; **no intersegment revenue** for Space. |\n| **Connectivity** | **(Relies on Space)** | Depends on Space for satellite deployment to operate its network. | Capitalizes launch costs received from Space. |\n| **AI** | **(Relies on Space)** | Plans to rely on Space for future launch needs. | (Future: Expected to capitalize launch costs.) |\n| **Corporate/Shared** | **All Segments** | Shared SG&A functions (legal, finance, HR, IT) are allocated across segments. | Allocated costs included in each segment\'s SG&A expenses. |\n\n### **Key Disclosures from the Text**\n\n*   "We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future."\n*   "For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites..."\n*   "Our Space segment revenue only reflects customer launches and customer activities." (Indicating internal launches are not reported as revenue).\n*   The CODM allocates resources and measures performance based on **segment income (loss) from operations**, which inherently considers the strategic value and costs of these interdependencies.\n\n**Conclusion:** The primary interdependency is a **cost-sharing and resource-allocation model** where the **Space segment acts as