        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'Retrieve information about GAAP segment reporting methodology from {{spaceX_s1}}. Look for: (1) how intersegment transactions are measured and eliminated, (2) the segment reporting policies and any limitations of GAAP segment presentation, (3) how transfer pricing or cost allocation methodology works for internal launches, (4) whether there are non-GAAP segment measures or reconciliations that might better capture interdependencies, and (5) any risk factors or discussion about the difficulty of evaluating individual segment performance due to interdependencies.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# GAAP Segment Reporting Methodology\n\n## 1. Intersegment Transactions: Measurement and Elimination\n\nThe document provides several key details about how intersegment transactions are handled:\n\n**Consolidation basis:** The consolidated financial statements include accounts of the Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries, with **all intercompany balances and transactions eliminated in consolidation** (Note 2 — Significant Accounting Policies).\n\n**Starlink launches — no inter-segment revenue recognized:** For launches of Starlink satellites, the Company **does not recognize any inter-segment revenue**. Instead, those launch costs are **capitalized in satellites in "Property, plant, and equipment, net."** This means the cost of internal launches flows to the Connectivity segment\'s balance sheet as a capital asset rather than through the Space segment\'s revenue.\n\n**Launch capacity allocation:** The Company "allocate[s] a significant amount of launch capacity to [the] Connectivity segment, and expect[s] to allocate a significant amount to [the] AI segment in the future." Critically, **Space segment revenue only reflects customer launches and customer activities** — internal launches are excluded from Space revenue entirely.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Segment Reporting Policies and Limitations of GAAP Presentation\n\n**Reportable segments:** The Company reports three segments — **Space, Connectivity, and AI** — with the GAAP primary measure being **Income (loss) from operations** at the segment level.\n\n**GAAP compliance:** Financial statements are prepared in accordance with U.S. GAAP, and management acknowledges that preparation requires "estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities" including revenues recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method.\n\n**Limitations explicitly acknowledged:**\n- Other companies may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently or not at all, "limiting their usefulness as comparative measures."\n- These measures "should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP."\n- They "should be considered together with our GAAP financial measures and the reconciliations to the corresponding most directly comparable GAAP financial measures."\n\n---\n\n## 3. Transfer Pricing and Cost Allocation for Internal Launches\n\nThis is one of the more revealing aspects of the filing. The methodology works as follows:\n\n**No transfer pricing in the traditional sense:** The Company does not use a market-based or cost-plus transfer price for inter-segment launches. Instead, internal Starlink launch costs bypass the revenue/expense recognition cycle entirely and are **directly capitalized as property, plant, and equipment** in the Connectivity segment.\n\n**Shared costs in Space segment:** Space segment cost of revenue includes "shared costs incurred in the production of launch hardware," suggesting some costs are allocated across purposes (customer vs. internal launches), though the exact allocation methodology is not specified in these excerpts.\n\n**Cost-to-cost input method for external contracts:** For Launch and Development contracts (primarily government), revenue is recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method, where revenue is recorded "based upon costs (such as materials and labor hours) incurred to date relative to the total estimated cost at completion." This requires significant management judgment including "assumptions regarding launch timing, labor hours, allocation of shared costs for launch vehicles that have been identified as reusable for multiple launches, as well as expected technological changes."\n\n**Reusability accounting:** Reusable components (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules) are classified as property, plant, and equipment and depreciated to cost of revenue. Non-reusable second stages are recorded to cost of revenue when launched. Starship costs are currently expensed to R&D.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Non-GAAP Segment Measures and Reconciliations\n\n**Segment Adjusted EBITDA** is the primary non-GAAP segment measure, defined as:\n\n> Segment income (loss) from operations **excluding**:\n> (i) depreciation and amortization\n> (ii) share-based compensation\n> (iii) restructuring charges\n> (iv) impairment\n\n**Consolidated Adjusted EBITDA** adds further adjustments:\n\n> Net income (loss) **excluding**:\n> (i) depreciation and amortization\n> (ii) share-based compensation\n> (iii) impairment\n> (iv) restructuring charges\n> (v) interest expense\n> (vi) interest income\n> (vii) other income (expense), net\n> (viii) provision for income taxes\n\n**Reconciliation tables are provided** showing both consolidated (net income → Adjusted EBITDA) and segment-level (segment income/loss from operations → Segment Adjusted EBITDA) reconciliations for the three months ended March 31, 2026 and the years ended December 31, 2025, 2024, and 2023.\n\n**Why non-GAAP measures may better capture interdependencies:**\n- By stripping out depreciation and amortization, Segment Adjusted EBITDA neutralizes differences caused by varying capital intensity across segments — particularly relevant given that the Space segment\'s reusable assets are depreciated while internal launches capitalize costs elsewhere.\n- Management considers these "meaningful performance measures for investors to evaluate our operating performance and to compare the financial results" across periods.\n- They are used "to assess our financial performance as well as for internal planning and forecasting purposes."\n\n**Illustrative example from Q1 2026:**\n\n| Segment | GAAP Income (Loss) from Operations | Segment Adjusted EBITDA |\n|---------|-----------------------------------|------------------------|\n| Space | $(662)M | $(351)M |\n| Connectivity | $1,188M | $2,087M |\n| AI | $(2,469)M | $(609)M |\n| **Total** | **$(1,943)M** | **$1,127M** |\n\nThe gap between GAAP and non-GAAP is most pronounced in Connectivity ($899M difference from D&A alone) and AI ($1,493M in D&A), reflecting the heavy capital investment in those segments.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Risk Factors and Difficulty of Evaluating Individual Segment Performance\n\nWhile the full risk factors section is not included in these excerpts, several passages highlight the **structural difficulty of evaluating individual segment performance**:\n\n**Interdependency challenges:**\n- The Space segment\'s financial performance is **artificially depressed** on a GAAP basis because it does not recognize revenue from internal launches that benefit Connectivity (and soon AI). The segment "only reflects our customer launches and customer activities."\n- Conversely, the Connectivity segment\'s cost structure **does not fully reflect the launch costs** it consumes, since those are capitalized rather than flowing through as an operating expense tied to Space revenue.\n- The AI segment is acquiring "a significant amount" of future launch capacity, creating another layer of interdependency.\n\n**Stage-of-development distortions:**\n- The AI segment was acquired in February 2026 and reflects "its earlier stage of development and continued investments to support long-term growth opportunities." Management explicitly warns of "a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA."\n- Starship is "currently in the development stage" with costs expensed to R&D, meaning Space segment results do not yet reflect the full economics of the next-generation vehicle.\n\n**Investment risk warning:** The document states plainly that "Investing in our Class A common stock involves a high degree of risk" and that "the disclosures reflect our beliefs and opinions as to factors that could materially and adversely affect us in the future. We may not be able to accurately predict, control, or mitigate these risks."\n\n**Capital expenditure concentration:** Q1 2026 capital expenditures were heavily concentrated in AI ($7,723M of $10,107M total), suggesting that segment-level profitability metrics may be dominated by investment timing rather than underlying operating performance.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe filing reveals a segment reporting structure where **GAAP measures alone provide an incomplete picture** of individual segment performance due to: (1) unrecorded inter-segment revenue for internal launches, (2) capitalization of launch costs to the consuming segment\'s balance sheet rather than through segment operating results, (3) varying stages of capital investment maturity across segments, and (4) shared cost allocations that require significant management judgment. The non-GAAP Segment Adjusted EBITDA measure partially addresses this by normalizing for depreciation and non-cash charges, but management cautions it should be used alongside — not as a substitute for — GAAP measures.',
